Prolog
“I beg you!” pleaded Queen Eirwen, “don’t send her away! She’s still a child!” The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his gaze darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair streaked with blue. A girl meant weakness to the Ice King. Up until this point, he had only produced sons.
You have two options: either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is your punishment for your failure, Eirwen,” he spat out her name as if it were venomous. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always one single kingdom. Earlier, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. The North was the non-magical kingdom, while the South was a kingdom filled with fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and there was an endless war between the two kingdoms until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the south was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the north, where she should bear a son, the future king. In this case, the north would unite with the south into one kingdom. The north accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my king, do whatever you wish with me, imprison me, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, with her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen with disgust. Perhaps, maybe, he might show her mercy. On the woman who had stood by him for 22 years, who had supported him through his darkest times, and who had given him his sons.
"Fine. The child can stay in the palace," he said, which was taken note of by the queen with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the floor. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the daughter of Queen Eirwen to one of Eirwen's free rooms. Then, he commanded the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution site, where all the city's citizens could watch.
While the guards escorted her to the execution site, there was a loud commotion among the citizens as they realized their beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Still others wondered why this was happening, but everyone agreed on one thing.
"Let her go free!"
"Why is this being done to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman who had just been queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the most terrible thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and refused to accept his words. Then the executioner lit the stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
“Don't give up, Kari.” This was the end of Queen Eirwen's regency.
Total silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the room located far to the left in the south wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants passing by wondered what was in that room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors circulated among the maids. Allegedly, the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room waiting to be released.
Her assumption couldn't have been more wrong, thought Ivory as she headed towards the south wing, while the servants passed by and whispered to each other. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors naturally also concerned Ivory, since she was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Tap, tap. "Lady Kari, are you in there?", whispered Ivory before the door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered whether, unlike the last time, entry would actually be granted. I still have bruises from the last time, she thought with a giggle. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, but apologized immediately when she realized who she had hit.
A single tap came from inside, likely to say that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I enter?", asked Ivory. Earlier, she had simply walked in without asking.
A ivory heard a knocking from within. This likely meant a "yes". The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound from what was supposedly an empty room, although Ivory had been entering it for several years already.
“I come in,” said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Papers were scattered everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little to no light. Additionally, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as though a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blankets, and reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
“Which notebook is that?” asked Ivory and sat beside Kari on the bed.
